Scott, chief lobbyist for the Advanced Medical Technology Association, said his group is "cautiously optimistic" that lawmakers will agree to the repeal the tax on devices, which he said cost the industry $2 billion in taxes this year. The tax is expected to raise nearly $30 billion for the federal government over the coming decade and affects products ranging from stents and hip replacement parts to surgical gloves.
